          "body": "The Shunammite episode is the chapter's theological center and longest narrative. It spans three scenes: hospitality and promise (4:8-17), crisis and intercession (4:18-30), and resurrection (4:31-37). The woman is described as *gadol* ('prominent' or 'great,' 4:8) — she has resources, social standing, and a husband; she lacks a son and, silently, expects nothing (4:13). When Elisha announces a son will be born 'at the appointed season' (*moed*, 4:16), she refuses to hope — 'do not lie to your maidservant' (4:16). The birth fulfills the word exactly (4:17). Then the child dies (4:20). Her response is extraordinary: she lays the body on Elisha's bed (4:21), tells her husband nothing specific (4:23), answers all questions with *shalom* (4:23, 26), and rides without pause to the prophet. Her lament when she reaches him (4:28) is not faithlessness but covenant honesty: 'Did I ask for a son? Did I not say, do not deceive me?' — she is holding the prophet accountable to the word he spoke. When Gehazi's staff fails (4:31), she refuses to leave the prophet (4:30), and Elisha goes in person. His prayer (4:33) and double act of stretching himself over the child (4:34-35) result in the sevenfold sneeze and the child's opened eyes. The Shunammite's worship — 'she fell at his feet and bowed herself to the ground' (4:37) — is the fitting close: the one who provided a room for the prophet receives back her son from the LORD who uses the prophet."
